KNOWING OUR "MAS" TO TRAIN VERY HARD üî•
Very hard training is this which make us barely breathe, that we can only mantain during short perioods but which has grear benefits. Improving this zone means improve all the less intensive zones above it. When we train at this intensity we should know our Maximal Aerobic Speed (MAS). It corresponds to VO2max speed which equals our HRmax. It's in line with Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP) very used in cycling. We can find it through a maximal test, as a medical one. To train very intrensive we should keep this or a very similar pace.

CLIMBING ON BIKE üö¥

Despite the fact that most triathlons has a flat cycling track, there are a lot of cycling races and high quality triathlons that climb prestigious hills. For that kind of competitions, it's good adding hard hilly workouts in your schedule, completing long climbs of 6-12km and accumulating 1500-2000m of final slope. If you prefer beast mode, you can try with very hard hilly sessions, climbing long hills of 13-20km. üì∑: Eric Besora
